Steveyboi 2/18/2024 11:24 AM
i'm bored so i decided to compare the english U8 and U16 manuals side by side and spot differences (not including paragraph position, justification and spacing and image differences) 1. (1-1, 3-12) U16 has different CPU core types which have different execution cycles for when a branch condition is met; 3 for A33/A34, 2 for A35. A34 is used by default. 2. (1-11) U8 has no word alignment for the stack, U16 does (SP is always forced to be even). this probably won't affect U16 programs run on U8, unless the programmer used assembly code and has terrible stack management skills. 3. (1-36) reading and writing dummy bytes when pushing and popping single byte data was reworded; on U8, pushing will trigger "a dummy cycle that decrements SP without saving any other registers", which will also write "an indeterminate byte of data to the stack", and popping is basically the same but in reverse, though there is no mention of reading an indeterminate byte. on U16, pushing will "store contexts of those operand with a dummy byte", and popping will "read a dummy byte without restoring any registers". 4. (3-11) condition 1 of a wait cycle was reworded slightly; "number of bytes accessed" was changed to "number of accesses" and "accessing a single byte" was changed to "single access". "Rom window" grammatical errors were also fixed in U16. 5. (section 3.3, section 4) most instructions have reduced minimum execution time in U16 (expected) 6. (3-74) if ELEVEL is 0, MOV Rn, EPSW will not change the value of Rn on U8. on U16 Rn is set to #FFH. 7. (3-82, 3-84, 3-85, 3-87) mentions of no auto word alignment for the stack were removed in U16 (obviously) 8. (3-84, 3-87) the "Stack Modifications" section in chapter 1 is mentioned on these pages in both manuals, however the U8 manual incorrectly labeled it as section 1.6. the U16 manual corrected this. 9. (4-5) the minimum execution times for the conditional branch instructions are all grouped together in U16. (edited)
1
11:30 AM
also worth noting: both manuals still have the "carry out of bit 15" error on page 3-38. this error is only in the english version and does not appear in the japanese or chinese versions. (edited)

Is there any way to cause a reset by software?

There are following two ways to cause a reset by software. (1) Reset by BRK instruction U8/U16 microcontroller has BRK instruction for CPU reset. Using this BRK instruction enables a reset by software. Note that BRK instruction causes CPU reset only, and peripheral functions such as SFR will not be reset. The following shows a description example in C source. #pragma asm mov psw, #02h brk #pragma endasm (2) Reset by WDT overflow CPU and peripheral circuits such as SFR are reset by causing a WDT overflow intentionally (WDTP not cleared). Note that it takes time to cause a WDT overflow. (edited)
